'''Cheryl Ann Tweedy'''<ref>{{cite web|last1=Harp|first1=Justin|title=Cheryl officially drops Fernandez-Versini surname|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/showbiz/news/a828759/cheryl-tweedy-drops-fernandez-versini-surname/|website=[[Digital Spy]]|publisher=[[Hearst Corporation]]|accessdate=20 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170520125329/http://www.digitalspy.com/showbiz/news/a828759/cheryl-tweedy-drops-fernandez-versini-surname/|archivedate=20 May 2017|location=United Kingdom|language=en|date=19 May 2017|quote=Her name is officially Cheryl Tweedy now, but to be honest it doesn't really bother me, we have a kid together, there's a lot more to our life.}}</ref> (born 30 June 1983) is an English singer, songwriter and television personality. Born and raised in [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], she rose to fame in late 2002 upon winning a place in [[Girls Aloud]], a [[girl group]] created through [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]'s ''[[Popstars: The Rivals]]''. While still in the group, she began a solo career in April 2009, and between then and 2014, she released four studio albums – ''[[3 Words]]'' (2009), ''[[Messy Little Raindrops]]'' (2010), ''[[A Million Lights]]'' (2012) and ''[[Only Human (Cheryl album)|Only Human]]'' (2014). Collectively, the albums included ten [[Cheryl discography#As lead artist|singles]], five of which – "[[Fight for This Love]], "[[Promise This]]", "[[Call My Name (Cheryl Cole song)|Call My Name]]", "[[Crazy Stupid Love (song)|Crazy Stupid Love]]" and "[[I Don't Care (Cheryl Cole song)|I Don't Care]]" – reached the [[Lists of UK Singles Chart number ones|top position]] on the [[UK Singles Chart]]. Cheryl was the first British female solo artist to have five number-one singles in the UK, and she held the record for the British female solo artist with the most UK number-one singles until [[Jess Glynne]] overtook her in 2018.

Cheryl became a judge on the [[The X Factor (UK TV series)|UK version]] of ''[[The X Factor]]'' in 2008. She mentored two of the eventual winners of the competition ([[Alexandra Burke]] in [[The X Factor (UK series 5)|series five]] and [[Joe McElderry]] in [[The X Factor (UK series 6)|series six]]), before resigning in 2011 and joining the panel of the [[The X Factor (U.S.)|American version]], which she left during the auditions stage. She returned to judge series [[The X Factor (UK series 11)|11]] and [[The X Factor (UK series 12)|12]] of the UK version.

Cheryl has become a recognised and photographed style [[icon]], being referred to as a "fashionista" by the press.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2009/jan/07/cheryl-cole-interview-vogue|title=Fashion Statement: Cheryl causes controversy|last=Holmes|first=Rachel|date=8 January 2009|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=10 May 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171126191359/https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2009/jan/07/cheryl-cole-interview-vogue|archivedate=26 November 2017}}</ref> She has been photographed for the covers of ''[[Vogue (British magazine)|British Vogue]]'', ''[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]'' and ''[[Harper's Bazaar]]'', and fronted cosmetic company [[L'Oréal]] in 2009.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/fashion/fashionnews/6096652/Cheryl-Cole-lands-LOreal-deal---because-shes-worth-it.html|title=Cheryl Cole lands L'Oréal deal – because she's worth it|last=Irvine|first=Chris|date=27 August 2009|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|access-date=10 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090831072912/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/fashion/fashionnews/6096652/Cheryl-Cole-lands-LOreal-deal---because-shes-worth-it.html|archive-date=31 August 2009|dead-url=y}}</ref> Her net worth was estimated at [[Pound sterling|£]]20&nbsp;million in October 2014.<ref name="Wealth12">{{cite web|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/business/business-opinion/cheryl-fernandez-versini-assets-reportedly-10750418|title=What will divorce do to the £20m assets of Cheryl Fernandez-Versini?|last=Leyshon|first=Charlotte|date=18 January 2016|website=walesonline|accessdate=12 June 2016|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701063858/http://www.walesonline.co.uk/business/business-opinion/cheryl-fernandez-versini-assets-reportedly-10750418|archivedate=1 July 2016}}</ref><ref name="Wealth22">{{cite web|url=http://www.spearswms.com/cheryl-cole-net-worth/|title=Cheryl Cole net worth|date=13 March 2016|website=Spear's Magazine|accessdate=12 June 2016|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161202211005/http://www.spearswms.com/cheryl-cole-net-worth/|archivedate=2 December 2016}}</ref> Cheryl was married to [[England national football team|England]] [[Association football|footballer]] [[Ashley Cole]] from July 2006 to September 2010. She married Jean-Bernard Fernandez-Versini in July 2014, and was granted a [[decree nisi]] from him in October 2016. From 2016 to 2018, she was in a relationship with [[One Direction]] singer [[Liam Payne]], with whom she has a son born in March 2017.

==Early life==
Cheryl Ann Tweedy<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/cheryl-cole-changes-her-name-to-cheryl-fernandezversini-after-marriage-to-jeanbernard-9606690.html|title=Cheryl Cole changes her name to Cheryl Fernandez-Versini after marriage to Jean-Bernard|last=Alexander|first=Ella|date=15 July 2014|work=[[The Independent]]|publisher=Independent Print Limited|accessdate=15 July 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715192749/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/cheryl-cole-changes-her-name-to-cheryl-fernandezversini-after-marriage-to-jeanbernard-9606690.html|archivedate=15 July 2014}}</ref> was born in [[Newcastle upon Tyne]] on 30 June 1983,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/cheryl-cole-mn0003331193|title=Cheryl Cole|publisher=[[AllMusic.com]]|accessdate=30 November 2016|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161201090507/http://www.allmusic.com/artist/cheryl-cole-mn0003331193|archivedate=1 December 2016}}</ref> and grew up on [[council estate]]s in the suburbs of [[Walker, Newcastle upon Tyne|Walker]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://women.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/women/celebrity/article5299070.ece|title=Superstar Cheryl Cole overcomes council estate adversity|first= Giles|last=Hattersley|work=The Times|date=7 December 2008|accessdate=9 May 2010|location=London}}{{dead link|date=May 2017}}</ref> and [[Heaton, Newcastle|Heaton]]. She is the fourth of five children of Joan Callaghan,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-news/7313494/Cheryl-Cole-comforted-by-Nicola-Roberts-as-Ashley-claims-couples-sex-life-had-dried-up.html|title=Cheryl Cole comforted by Nicola Roberts as Ashley claims couple's sex life had dried up|work=The Daily Telegraph|first=Heide|last=Blake|date=25 February 2010|accessdate=9 May 2010|location=London|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100228181425/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-news/7313494/Cheryl-Cole-comforted-by-Nicola-Roberts-as-Ashley-claims-couples-sex-life-had-dried-up.html|archivedate=28 February 2010}}</ref> and the first of her two children with Garry Tweedy following the collapse of her marriage to the father of her three other children. Cheryl's parents were together for more than a decade but never married; they separated when she was 11 years old.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/north-east-news/todays-evening-chronicle/2008/10/03/cheryl-cole-reveals-all-about-girls-aloud-fame-72703-21958013|title=Cheryl Cole reveals all about Girls Aloud fame|last=Lamb|first=Liz|date=3 October 2008|work=[[Evening Chronicle]]|access-date=10 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007055803/http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/north-east-news/todays-evening-chronicle/2008/10/03/cheryl-cole-reveals-all-about-girls-aloud-fame-72703-21958013|archive-date=7 October 2008|dead-url=y}}</ref>

At the age of seven, Cheryl appeared in a television advert for [[British Gas]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/8521987.stm|title=Cheryl Cole's life in the spotlight|last=|first=|date=6 July 2010|work=[[BBC News]]|access-date=10 May 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170823182115/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/8521987.stm|archivedate=23 August 2017}}</ref> Interested in dancing from an early age, she began [[sequence dancing]] at the age of four,<ref>Smith, S (2009) ''Cheryl'', Simon & Schuster UK<!-- ISBN needed, pages needed --></ref> before joining [[The Royal Ballet]]'s summer school at the age of nine.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/tv_and_radio/3207926.stm|title=Girls Aloud's year at the top|publisher=BBC News|date=20 October 2003|accessdate=26 August 2008|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060620133157/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/tv_and_radio/3207926.stm|archivedate=20 June 2006}}</ref> She occasionally appeared doing dance recitals on different television shows in the UK, such as ''[[Gimme 5]]'', in 1993.<ref>{{cite news |first=Lisa |last=Hutchinson |url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/showbiz-news/23-things-you-didnt-know-11254405 |title=23 things you didn't know about our very own Geordie pop princess Cheryl |publisher= |newspaper=Chronicle Live |date=28 April 2016 |accessdate=1 May 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160704062858/http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/showbiz-news/23-things-you-didnt-know-11254405 |archivedate=4 July 2016  }}</ref>

==Career==

===2002–2009: ''Popstars: The Rivals'' and Girls Aloud===

{{see also|Popstars: The Rivals|Girls Aloud}}
[[File:Girls Aloud at Rock On! by David Jones.jpg|thumbnail|left|250px|Cheryl (far right) with Girls Aloud performing at the Capital Radio Help a London Child fundraiser, 2005.]]
Cheryl auditioned for the reality television show ''[[Popstars: The Rivals]]'' in 2002, which aimed to create a [[boy band]] and a [[girl group]] to compete for the [[Lists of UK number one singles|Christmas number one]] spot on the [[UK Singles Chart]]. She sang "[[Have You Ever (S Club 7 song)|Have You Ever]]" in her audition,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/nov/09/girlsaloud-thexfactor|title=The nation's new sweetheart|work=The Guardian|accessdate=12 November 2008|location=London|first=Elizabeth|last=Day|date=9 November 2008|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140213165743/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/nov/09/girlsaloud-thexfactor|archivedate=13 February 2014}}</ref> and was one of twenty contestants (ten girls and ten boys) chosen as finalists by judges [[Pete Waterman]], [[Louis Walsh]] and [[Geri Halliwell]]. The finalists performed live on Saturday evenings, with one gender performing each week, and each week the contestant polling the fewest phone votes was eliminated, until the final line-ups of the five-piece groups emerged. Cheryl was in danger of elimination twice, surviving over [[Clea (band)|Emma Beard]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/popstars/news/a9505/emma-chloe-voted-out-in-popstars-the-rivals/|title=Emma, Chloe  voted out in 'Popstars: The Rivals'|date=2 November 2002|work=Digital Spy|accessdate=31 May 2016|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822042150/http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/popstars/news/a9505/emma-chloe-voted-out-in-popstars-the-rivals/|archivedate=22 August 2016}}</ref> and Aimee Kearsley<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/popstars/news/a9611/aimee-out-in-popstars/|title=Aimee out in 'Popstars'|date=16 November 2002|work=Digital Spy|accessdate=31 May 2016|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160722180814/http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/popstars/news/a9611/aimee-out-in-popstars/|archivedate=22 July 2016}}</ref> in consecutive performing weeks. On 30 November 2002, she was the first contestant to qualify for the girl group, and was joined by [[Nadine Coyle]], [[Sarah Harding]], [[Nicola Roberts]] and [[Kimberley Walsh]] to form [[Girls Aloud]], following the final public vote.<ref name="popstars">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/tv_and_radio/2532667.stm|title=Popstars 'vote blunder' denied|date=2 December 2002|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=1 November 2010|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071217061820/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/tv_and_radio/2532667.stm|archivedate=17 December 2007}}</ref> The group's debut single "[[Sound of the Underground (song)|Sound of the Underground]]" peaked at number one on the UK Singles Chart, becoming the 2002 Christmas number one over boy band [[One True Voice]]'s "[[Sacred Trust / After You're Gone]]".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/2599721.stm|title=Girls Aloud top festive chart|date=23 December 2002|accessdate=24 February 2008|publisher=BBC News|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081207112208/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/2599721.stm|archivedate=7 December 2008}}</ref> Girls Aloud hold the record for the shortest time between being formed as a band and achieving a number one single.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theinsider.com/news/489272_Cheryl_Cole_Attending_Kimberley_Walsh_26th_Brithday_Party |title=Cheryl Cole Attending Kimberley Walsh 26th Brithday Party|work=The Insider|date=26 November 2007|accessdate=11 June 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090817120451/http://www.theinsider.com/news/489272_Cheryl_Cole_Attending_Kimberley_Walsh_26th_Brithday_Party|archivedate=17 August 2009}}</ref>

Girls Aloud released their debut album ''[[Sound of the Underground (Girls Aloud album)|Sound of the Underground]]'' in May 2003,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/popstars/a11004/girls-aloud-prepare-for-album-release.html|title=Girls Aloud prepare for album release|first=Neil|last=Wilkes|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=30 April 2003|accessdate=9 May 2010|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66SXH55xy?url=http://www.digitalspy.com/british-tv/s102/popstars/news/a11004/girls-aloud-prepare-for-album-release.html|archivedate=26 March 2012}}</ref> which entered the charts at number two and was certified platinum by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] (BPI) later the same year. Their singles "[[I'll Stand by You#Girls Aloud version|I'll Stand by You]]", "[[Walk This Way#Sugababes vs. Girls Aloud|Walk This Way]]", and "[[The Promise (Girls Aloud song)|The Promise]]" charted at number one. Two of their albums reached the top of the [[UK Albums Chart]]: their [[greatest hits album]] ''[[The Sound of Girls Aloud]]'' and 2008's ''[[Out of Control (Girls Aloud album)|Out of Control]]'', both of which entered the chart at number one, with over one million copies of the former being sold.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?sectioncode=1&storycode=1036788&c=1|title=Take That shine among IFPI Platinum elite|work=Music Week|publisher=United Business Media|date=29 January 2009|accessdate=30 January 2009|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66SXRfIAH?url=http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?sectioncode=1&storycode=1036788&c=1|archivedate=26 March 2012}}</ref>
They also achieved seven certified albums and were nominated for five [[Brit Awards]], winning the 2009 Best Single for "The Promise".<ref name="bestsingle">{{cite web|url=http://www.brits.co.uk/news/the-promise-by-girls-aloud-is/|title=The Promise by Girls Aloud is the 2009 British Single|work=[[The Brit Awards]]|publisher=British Phonographic Industry|date=18 February 2009|accessdate=26 November 2009|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091129065843/http://www.brits.co.uk/news/the-promise-by-girls-aloud-is/|archivedate=29 November 2009}}</ref> The group's musical style was pop, but throughout their career they experimented with [[electropop]] and [[dance-pop]]. Girls Aloud's collaborations with [[Brian Higgins (producer)|Brian Higgins]] and his songwriting and production team [[Xenomania]] earned the group critical acclaim,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polydor.co.uk/topstories.php?story=56|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130421044546/http://www.polydor.co.uk/topstories.php?story=56|dead-url=yes|archive-date=21 April 2013|title=Yeah Yeah Yeah's – Top Stories – Polydor Records|date=21 April 2013|publisher=|accessdate=9 April 2017}}</ref> due to an innovative approach to [[Mainstream#In music|mainstream]] pop music. The group amassed a fortune of [[£]]30&nbsp;million by May 2010. ''[[Guinness World Records]]'' lists them as "Most Successful Reality TV Group" in the 2007 edition. They also hold the record for "Most Consecutive Top Ten Entries in the UK by a Female Group" in the 2008 edition, and are credited again for "Most Successful Reality TV Group" in the 2011 edition. The group was also named the United Kingdom's biggest selling girl group of the 21st century, with over 4.3&nbsp;million singles sales and 4 million albums sold in the UK alone.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/girls-aloud-crowned-the-biggest-selling-girl-group-of-the-21st-century-1652/|title=Girls Aloud crowned the biggest selling girl group of the 21st Century.|publisher=British Phonographic Industry|date=18 October 2012|accessdate=27 December 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121227123350/http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/girls-aloud-crowned-the-biggest-selling-girl-group-of-the-21st-century-1652/|archivedate=27 December 2012}}</ref><ref name="sales">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/1554238/girls-aloud-a-whole-lotta-chart-history|title=Girls Aloud: A Whole Lotta Chart History|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=21 March 2013|accessdate=21 March 2013|work=Billboard|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130325063723/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/1554238/girls-aloud-a-whole-lotta-chart-history|archivedate=25 March 2013}}</ref> Girls Aloud took a [[Recess (break)|hiatus]] in 2009 in the pursuit of solo projects, saying they would reunite for a new studio album in 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/girls-aloud/46150|title=Girls Aloud deny split rumours|work=[[NME]]|date=16 July 2009|accessdate=3 September 2009|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66SXbeF99?url=http://www.nme.com/news/girls-aloud/46150|archivedate=26 March 2012}}</ref> but this did not materialise.

===2008–2011: Television endeavours, ''3 Words'' and ''Messy Little Raindrops''===

[[File:Cheryl Cole, Hastings.jpg|thumb|upright=0.75|alt=With her brown hair tied back, a female wearing a glittery outfit is performing with a headset microphone.|Cheryl during a live performance at [[Battle Abbey]] in [[Hastings]], August 2008]]
In 2008, Cheryl replaced [[Sharon Osbourne]] as a judge for the [[The X Factor (UK series 5)|fifth series]] of ''The X Factor'' alongside creator [[Simon Cowell]], [[Dannii Minogue]] and Louis Walsh. She was given the girls category (made up of female solo contestants aged 16 to 25) and subsequently ended up as the winning judge when [[Alexandra Burke]] was crowned the winner of series five on 13 December.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7782054.stm|title=Alexandra crowned X Factor winner|date=14 December 2008|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=28 June 2009|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090218005159/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7782054.stm|archivedate=18 February 2009}}</ref> She returned for the [[The X Factor (UK series 6)|sixth series]] in 2009 and was given the boys category (made up of male solo contestants aged 16 to 25).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/xfactor/a179357/x-factor-judges-given-their-categories.html|title='X Factor' judges given their categories|first=Catriona|last=Wightman|date=27 October 2009|accessdate=27 October 2009|work=Digital Spy|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091031003541/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/xfactor/a179357/x-factor-judges-given-their-categories.html|archivedate=31 October 2009}}</ref> She was the winning judge for a second consecutive year when [[Joe McElderry]] won on 13 December.<ref>{{cite web|title=Joe McElderry wins British X-Factor|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/12/14/2770529.htm|publisher=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]|date=14 December 2009|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628230221/http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/12/14/2770529.htm|archivedate=28 June 2011}}</ref> Cowell referred to her as "one of the best I've ever worked with."<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://celebrity.uk.msn.com/news/articles.aspx?cp-documentid=151996410|title=Simon: Cheryl's one of the best|last=|first=|date=2 February 2010|work=[[Press Association]]/[[MSN]]|access-date=10 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100206211721/http://celebrity.uk.msn.com/news/articles.aspx?cp-documentid=151996410|archive-date=6 February 2010|dead-url=y}}</ref> Cheryl returned for the [[The X Factor (UK series 7)|seventh series]] in 2010 and mentored the girls category again.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/music/x-factor/news/238486-simon-tips-cheryl-to-win|title=Simon tips Cheryl to win|last=|first=|date=27 September 2010|work=[[MTV UK]]|access-date=10 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100930204203/http://www.mtv.co.uk/music/x-factor/news/238486-simon-tips-cheryl-to-win|archive-date=30 September 2010|dead-url=y}}</ref> This was the first series in which she was not the winning mentor, when [[Rebecca Ferguson (singer)|Rebecca Ferguson]] finished as runner-up to [[Matt Cardle]], who was mentored by Minogue. In 2011, Cheryl joined Cowell, [[L.A. Reid]], and [[Paula Abdul]] on the judging panel of the [[The X Factor (U.S.)|American version]] of ''The X Factor''.<ref name="Confirmed for X Factor US">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2011/may/05/cheryl-cole-us-x-factor-judge|title=Cheryl Cole confirmed as US X Factor judge'|last=Plunkett|first=John|date=5 May 2011|location=London|work=The Guardian|accessdate=5 May 2011|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130930083002/http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2011/may/05/cheryl-cole-us-x-factor-judge|archivedate=30 September 2013}}</ref> After a three-week stint she departed the series.<ref name="bbc.co.uk">{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/13675314|title=X Factor confirms Cheryl Cole not a judge in US show|publisher=BBC Newsbeat|accessdate=6 June 2011|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608125001/http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/13675314|archivedate=8 June 2011}}</ref> Cowell said that the reason why she left was because he offered her a place on the [[The X Factor (UK series 8)|2011 series of the UK version]] and he felt that she would have been more comfortable there.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2011/08/05/simon-cowell-x-factor-american-idol|title=Simon Cowell believes 'X Factor' can top 'Idol'|last=Hibberd|first=James|date=5 August 2011|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=10 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110816045130/http://insidetv.ew.com/2011/08/05/simon-cowell-x-factor-american-idol|archive-date=16 August 2011|dead-url=y}}</ref> Cheryl did not return to the UK version, as [[Tulisa]] had taken her place on the UK judging panel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nowmagazine.co.uk/celebrity-news/tv-news/524702/confirmed-n-dubz-s-tulisa-and-kelly-rowland-to-replace-cheryl-cole-and-dannii-minogue-on-the-x-factor/1|title=CONFIRMED N-Dubz's Tulisa and Kelly Rowland to replace Cheryl Cole and Dannii Minogue on The X Factor|date=31 May 2011|work=Now Magazine|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120119053110/http://www.nowmagazine.co.uk/celebrity-news/tv-news/524702/confirmed-n-dubz-s-tulisa-and-kelly-rowland-to-replace-cheryl-cole-and-dannii-minogue-on-the-x-factor/1|archivedate=19 January 2012}}</ref> [[Nicole Scherzinger]] replaced her on the judging panel of the American version for the rest of [[The X Factor (U.S. season 1)|season one]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://insidetv.ew.com:80/2011/06/06/nicole-scherzinger-cheryl-cole-the-x-factor/ |title=Official: Nicole Scherzinger replaces Cheryl Cole on 'The X-Factor' |last=Rice |first=Lynette |date=6 June 2011 |work=Entertainment Weekly |access-date=10 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609032102/http://insidetv.ew.com/2011/06/06/nicole-scherzinger-cheryl-cole-the-x-factor/ |archive-date=9 June 2011 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> In December 2012, Cheryl sued the American producers of ''The X Factor'' for $2.3&nbsp;million (£1.4m). She received $1.8&nbsp;million (£1.1m) for the first season, and then sued for $2&nbsp;million (£1.25m) for the second season, plus additional damages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/ustv/s141/the-x-factor-us/news/a443909/cheryl-cole-sues-x-factor-usa-producers-for-usd23-million.html|title=Cheryl Cole sues 'X Factor' USA producers for $2.3 million|work=Digital Spy|accessdate=1 March 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203025301/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/ustv/s141/the-x-factor-us/news/a443909/cheryl-cole-sues-x-factor-usa-producers-for-usd23-million.html|archivedate=3 December 2013}}</ref> In November 2013, Cheryl won for her settlement, for an undisclosed amount between her and producers Blue Orbit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/News/Cheryl-Cole-XFactor-Lawsuit-Payout-1074018.aspx|title=Fired ''X Factor'' Judge Cheryl Cole Wins Payout From Producers|last=Stanhope|first=Kate|date=28 November 2013|work=[[TV Guide]]|accessdate=29 November 2013|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131130104212/http://www.tvguide.com/News/Cheryl-Cole-XFactor-Lawsuit-Payout-1074018.aspx|archivedate=30 November 2013}}</ref>

Cheryl's first solo performance was on American rapper [[will.i.am]]'s "[[Heartbreaker (will.i.am song)|Heartbreaker]]" in 2008. She was picked to appear as a dancer in the video after taking [[Streetdance|streetdancing]] classes during the filming of [[ITV2]] series ''[[The Passions of Girls Aloud]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tourdates.co.uk/news/12053-cheryl-cole-records-with-william|title=Cheryl Cole records with Will.i.am|last=|first=|date=4 March 2008|work=tourdates.co.uk|access-date=10 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110811024247/http://www.tourdates.co.uk/news/12053-cheryl-cole-records-with-william|archive-date=11 August 2011|dead-url=y}}</ref> She was later asked by will.i.am to sing additional vocals on the track.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.myparkmag.co.uk/articles/entertainment/music/cheryl-cole-teams-up-with-william.html|title=Cheryl Cole teams up with Will.i.am|last=|first=|date=25 April 2008|work=My Park Magazine|access-date=10 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080501162957/http://www.myparkmag.co.uk/articles/entertainment/music/cheryl-cole-teams-up-with-william.html|archive-date=1 May 2008|dead-url=y}}</ref> In April 2009, she started working on solo material,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/artists/cheryl-cole/news/116962-cheryl-cole-confirms-solo-career|title=Cheryl Cole confirms solo career|date=27 April 2009|publisher=[[MTV News]]|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/679Sj6CXn?url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/news/cheryl-cole/116962-cheryl-cole-confirms-solo-career|archivedate=24 April 2012}}</ref> and her debut album, ''[[3 Words]]'', was released in the UK on 26 October.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.play.com/Music/CD/4-/11684687/Three-Words/Product.html|title=Cheryl Cole (Girls Aloud) – Three Words: CD|last=|first=|date=|website=[[play.com]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090912081526/http://www.play.com/Music/CD/4-/11684687/Three-Words/Product.html|archive-date=12 September 2009|dead-url=y|access-date=10 May 2017}}</ref> The album spent two weeks at number one,<ref name="chartstats1">{{cite web|url=http://www.chartstats.com/albuminfo.php?id=14510 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100303011209/http://www.chartstats.com/albuminfo.php?id=14510 |dead-url=yes |archive-date=3 March 2010 |title=Cheryl Cole – 3 Words |publisher=Chart Stats |accessdate=16 November 2009 |df= }}</ref> and on 6 November, BPI certified the album platinum, denoting shipments of over 300,000 units; it later tripled this feat.<ref name="bpi"/> The first single from the album, "[[Fight for This Love]]", was written by Andre Merritt, [[Steve Kipner]] and [[Wayne Wilkins]], and produced by Kipner and Wilkins. Following a performance on ''The X Factor'' live results show, "Fight for This Love" entered the UK and Irish charts at number one,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a183376/cheryl-cole-tops-irish-singles-chart.html |title=Cheryl Cole tops Irish singles chart |work=Digital Spy |first=Daniel |last=Kilkelly |date=23 October 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609223715/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a183376/cheryl-cole-tops-irish-singles-chart.html |archivedate=9 June 2011 |df= }}</ref> and in 2010, it went to number one in Denmark, Norway and Hungary,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://acharts.us/song/51174|title=Cheryl Cole – Fight For This Love|work=US Charts|accessdate=11 June 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/679SkpsFU?url=http://acharts.us/song/51174|archivedate=24 April 2012}}</ref> and was later certified platinum in the UK.<ref name="bpi">{{cite web |url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certified-awards.aspx |title=Certified Awards |format=''Enter the keywords "Cheryl Cole", select search by Artist, tick the "Exact match" box and click search'' |publisher=British Phonographic Industry |accessdate=16 October 2016  |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140625075145/http://www.bpi.co.uk/certified-awards.aspx |archivedate=25 June 2014 }}</ref> It also became the fourth best-selling single of 2009 in the UK.<ref name="2009 UK Year-End Charts">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com.au/music/news/a193480/gagas-poker-face-is-top-single-of-2009.html|title=2009 UK Year-End Charts|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502033325/http://www.digitalspy.com.au/music/news/a193480/gagas-poker-face-is-top-single-of-2009.html|archivedate=2 May 2014}}</ref> Cheryl's second single, "[[3 Words (song)|3 Words]]", which features will.i.am, went to number four in the UK and seven in Ireland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a192827/joe-mcelderry-climbs-up-to-number-one.html|title=Joe McElderry climbs up to number one|first=Catriona|last=Wightman|work=Digital Spy|date=27 December 2009|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/679XMAkCe?url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a192827/joe-mcelderry-climbs-up-to-number-one.html|archivedate=24 April 2012}}</ref><ref name="irish chart"/> In 2010, the single was released in Australia and charted at number five, and was certified platinum.<ref name="AUS2010 Singles">{{cite web|url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.auaccreds2010.htm |title=ARIA Charts – Accreditations – 2010 Singles |work=[[ARIA Charts]] |publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]] |accessdate=5 August 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64wvbyh3C?url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.auaccreds2010.htm |archivedate=25 January 2012  }}</ref> The third single, "[[Parachute (Cheryl Cole song)|Parachute]]", charted in the top five in both the UK and Ireland, and was certified gold in the UK.<ref name="uk chart">{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/28572/cheryl/|title=Cheryl|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref><ref name="irish chart"/><ref name="bpi"/>

[[File:Cheryl Cole and Simon Cowell.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Cheryl alongside [[Simon Cowell]] on ''[[The X Factor (UK)|The X Factor]]'', London, June 2010]]
Cheryl started recording sessions for her second album in February 2010,<ref name="youtube">{{Youtube|us6EPrD_kKM|Cheryl Cole Fan Interview}}</ref> though in an interview on ''[[Alan Carr: Chatty Man]]'', she said that some of the songs submitted for the record dated back to ''3 Words''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com:80/programmes/alan-carr-chatty-man/episode-guide/series-5/episode-2 |title=Alan Carr: Chatty Man – Series 5 – Episode 2 |last= |first= |date= |website=[[Channel 4]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101223123328/http://www.channel4.com/programmes/alan-carr-chatty-man/episode-guide/series-5/episode-2 |archive-date=23 December 2010 |dead-url=yes |access-date=10 May 2017 |df= }}</ref> The album was largely produced by Wayne Wilkins<ref name="productionMLR">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-cheryl-cole-messy-little-raindrops-polydor-2121608.html|title=Album: Cheryl Cole, Messy Little Raindrops (Polydor)|date=31 October 2010|publisher=Independent|location=London|author=Price, Simon|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170814215633/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-cheryl-cole-messy-little-raindrops-polydor-2121608.html|archivedate=14 August 2017}}</ref> and released on 29 October 2010 under the title ''[[Messy Little Raindrops]]''. It features guest vocals from [[August Rigo]], [[Dizzee Rascal]], [[Travie McCoy]], and will.i.am,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/artists/cheryl-cole/news/242200-cheryl-cole-new-album-cover-ashley-cole|title=Cheryl Cole unveils new album artwork|date=14 October 2010|publisher=MTV News|accessdate=1 November 2010|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101017052421/http://www.mtv.co.uk/artists/cheryl-cole/news/242200-cheryl-cole-new-album-cover-ashley-cole|archivedate=17 October 2010}}</ref> and debuted at number one in the UK, and at number two in Ireland.<ref name="uk chart"/><ref name="irish chart"/> It received generally mixed reviews from music critics, with a positive review of four out of five stars from Jon O'Brien of [[Allmusic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/messy-little-raindrops-r2066681/review|title=Messy Little Raindrops – Cheryl Cole|last=O'Brien|first=Jon|date=|website=AllMusic|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101112043657/http://www.allmusic.com/album/messy-little-raindrops-r2066681/review|archive-date=12 November 2010|dead-url=y|access-date=10 May 2017}}</ref> On 19 August 2011, the album was certified platinum by BPI, with shipments in the UK exceeding 300,000.<ref name="bpi"/> The album's first single, "[[Promise This]]", is an [[up-tempo]] dance-pop song written by Wilkins, [[Priscilla Renea|Priscilla Hamilton]] and Christopher Jackson,<ref name="booklet">{{cite AV media notes|title=Messy Little Raindrops|titlelink=Messy Little Raindrops|others=Cheryl Cole|year=2010|type=Booklet|publisher=[[Fascination Records|Fascination]], [[Polydor Records]] (Cat no. 2753287)|location=London, UK}}</ref><ref name="OK!">{{cite web|url=http://www.ok.co.uk/celebnews/view/26317/Ooo-Cheryl-Cole-s-new-single-Promise-This-is-unveiled|archive-url=https://archive.is/20140224205034/http://www.ok.co.uk/celebnews/view/26317/Ooo-Cheryl-Cole-s-new-single-Promise-This-is-unveiled|dead-url=yes|archive-date=24 February 2014|title=Ooo, Cheryl Cole's new single Promise This is unveiled!|date=14 September 2010|work=OK!|accessdate=23 September 2010}}</ref> which was released on 24 October 2010 and became her second number-one in the UK where it was certified gold.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/artists/cheryl-cole/news/244221-cheryl-cole-promise-this-number-1-rihanna-x-factor|title=Cheryl Cole Scores Second Solo Number 1|publisher=MTV|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606084158/http://www.mtv.co.uk/artists/cheryl-cole/news/244221-cheryl-cole-promise-this-number-1-rihanna-x-factor|archivedate=6 June 2011}}</ref> "[[The Flood (Cheryl Cole song)|The Flood]]" was released as the album's second single and entered the charts after its official release at number 18.<ref name="uk chart"/>

Cheryl was given a one-off television programme for [[ITV1]], ''[[Cheryl Cole's Night In]]'', which aired on 19 December 2009.<ref name="nightin">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/news/a187953/cheryl-cole-given-her-own-tv-show.html|title=Cheryl Cole given her own TV show|first=Rebecca|last=Routledge|date=21 November 2009|accessdate=22 November 2009|work=Digital Spy|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091126235728/http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/news/a187953/cheryl-cole-given-her-own-tv-show.html|archivedate=26 November 2009}}</ref> The programme, hosted by [[Holly Willoughby]], featured music and interviews with Cheryl and some of her favourite performers. Alexandra Burke, [[Rihanna]], [[Will Young]], [[Snow Patrol]] and will.i.am made appearances.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/Showbiz-News/Cheryl-Cole-Get-Own-One-Off-ITV1-Show-Singer-Will-Perform-With-Friends-On-Programme/Article/200911415463734?lpos=Showbiz_News_Third_UK_News_Article_Teaser_Region__4&lid=ARTICLE_15463734_Cheryl_Cole_Get_Own_One-Off_ITV1_Show%3A_Singer_Will_Perform_With_Friends_On_Programme |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091127054046/http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/Showbiz-News/Cheryl-Cole-Get-Own-One-Off-ITV1-Show-Singer-Will-Perform-With-Friends-On-Programme/Article/200911415463734?lpos=Showbiz_News_Third_UK_News_Article_Teaser_Region__4&lid=ARTICLE_15463734_Cheryl_Cole_Get_Own_One-Off_ITV1_Show%3A_Singer_Will_Perform_With_Friends_On_Programme |dead-url=yes |archive-date=27 November 2009 |title=Cheryl Cole gets her own one-off TV show |first=Elizabeth |last=Scott |publisher=[[Sky News]] |date=23 November 2009 |accessdate=23 November 2009 |df= }}</ref> The programme attracted 5 million viewers on its first airing.<ref>{{cite news|first=Chris|last=Tryhorn|title=TV ratings: More than 12m see Stacey eliminated from The X Factor|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/dec/14/tv-ratings-stacey-x-factor|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=14 December 2009|accessdate=20 December 2009|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140103030634/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/dec/14/tv-ratings-stacey-x-factor|archivedate=3 January 2014}}</ref>

From May to July 2010, Cheryl was the opening act for [[The Black Eyed Peas]] at the British shows (as well as some European dates) of [[The E.N.D. World Tour]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theglobalherald.com/cheryl-cole-to-tour-with-black-eyed-peas/1943/ |title=Cheryl Cole to tour with Black Eyed Peas|first=Nola M|last=Ojomu|work=The Global Herald|publisher=24 Hour Trading|date=29 January 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100131023449/http://theglobalherald.com/cheryl-cole-to-tour-with-black-eyed-peas/1943/|archivedate=31 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a199746/cheryl-cole-for-black-eyed-peas-uk-tour.html|title=Cheryl Cole 'for Black Eyed Peas UK tour'|first=Oli|last=Simpson|work=Digital Spy|date=27 January 2010|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/678TOLvlS?url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a199746/cheryl-cole-for-black-eyed-peas-uk-tour.html|archivedate=23 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blitz.aeiou.pt/gen.pl?p=stories&op=view&fokey=bz.stories/57472 |title=Black Eyed Peas trazem Cheryl Cole a Portugal |accessdate=18 February 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100221000535/http://blitz.aeiou.pt/gen.pl?p=stories&op=view&fokey=bz.stories%2F57472 |archivedate=21 February 2010 |df= }}</ref> Cheryl was interviewed during an episode of the fourth series of ''[[Piers Morgan's Life Stories]]'', in which she discussed her marriage and divorce with [[Ashley Cole]] and her life-threatening battle with [[malaria]]. The show, which aired on 23 October 2010, drew an audience of 7.2&nbsp;million, the highest figure in the chat show's history.<ref name="Lifestories">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/oct/25/cheryl-cole-piers-morgan-ratings|title=TV ratings: 7m tune in for Cheryl Cole on Piers Morgan's Life Stories|work=The Guardian|accessdate=28 October 2010|location=London|first=John|last=Plunkett|date=25 October 2010|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131204145318/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/oct/25/cheryl-cole-piers-morgan-ratings|archivedate=4 December 2013}}</ref>

===2012–2013: ''A Million Lights'', Girls Aloud reunion and tours===
Cheryl's third studio album, ''[[A Million Lights]]'', was released on 18 June 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cheryl Cole Unveils New Album 'A Million Lights' Tracklisting And Artwork|url=http://www.capitalfm.com/artists/cheryl-cole/news/new-album-a-million-lights-tracklisting-artwork/|work=[[Capital (radio network)|Capital FM]]|date=24 May 2012|accessdate=3 August 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170803220959/http://www.capitalfm.com/artists/cheryl-cole/news/new-album-a-million-lights-tracklisting-artwork/|archivedate=3 August 2017}}</ref> It debuted at number two on the UK Albums Chart, selling 34,934 copies in its first week on sale, and was her first not to debut at number one in the UK and her first not to sell over 100,000 copies in its first week.<ref name=":6">{{cite web|url=http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?sectioncode=1&storycode=1050081&c=1|title=Music Week Chart Analysis. Official Charts Analysis: Bieber beats Cheryl to No.1 by 38,181 sales 25 June 2012 By Alan Jones|work=Music Week|accessdate=4 August 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102231914/http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?sectioncode=1&storycode=1050081&c=1|archivedate=2 November 2013}}</ref> Her debut album ''3 Words'' sold 125,000 copies while its follow-up ''Messy Little Raindrops'' sold around 105,000 copies.<ref name=":6" /> ''A Million Lights'' was certified gold in the UK for shipments of 100,000 copies.<ref name="bpi"/> The lead single "[[Call My Name (Cheryl Cole song)|Call My Name]]", became Cheryl's third number one single on the UK Singles Chart, with the sales of 152,001 digital copies. The song became 2012's fastest selling number one single on the UK Singles Chart until December of the same year,<ref>{{cite web|title=Cheryl's Call My Name becomes 2012's fastest selling Number 1 single! |url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/cheryls-call-my-name-becomes-2012s-fastest-selling-number-1-single-1450/ |date=17 June 2012 |accessdate=17 June 2012 |last=Kreisler |first=Lauren |publisher=UK Singles Chart. Official Charts Company |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120619193221/http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/cheryls-call-my-name-becomes-2012s-fastest-selling-number-1-single-1450/ |archivedate=19 June 2012 |df= }}</ref> when the winner of [[The X Factor (UK series 9)|that year's series of ''The X Factor'']], [[James Arthur (singer)|James Arthur]], sold 490,560 copies with his cover of [[Shontelle]]'s "[[Impossible (Shontelle song)|Impossible]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/dec/17/james-arthur-fastest-selling-single|title=James Arthur scores fastest selling single of the year|work=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian News and Media|date=17 December 2012|accessdate=18 December 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130930220220/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/dec/17/james-arthur-fastest-selling-single|archivedate=30 September 2013}}</ref> "Call My Name" sold a total of 417,000 copies in the UK, and was the 34th best-selling single of 2012 there.<ref name="ukye">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/official-charts-advent-calendar-2012-day-15/|title=Official Charts Advent Calendar 2012: Day 15|first=Dan|last=Lane|publisher=UK Singles Chart. Official Chart Company|date=15 December 2012|accessdate=26 December 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121228205016/http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/official-charts-advent-calendar-2012-day-15/|archivedate=28 December 2012}}</ref> "[[Under the Sun (song)|Under the Sun]]", the second single from the album, was released on 2 September 2012,<ref name="UnderTheSun">{{cite web|url=http://www.entertainmentwise.com/news/79316/Cheryl-Cole-Confirms-Second-Single-From-A-Million-Lights |title=Cheryl Cole Confirms 'A Million Lights' Second Single |last=Kitchener |first=Shaun |publisher=Entertainmentwise.com |accessdate=24 June 2012 |date=24 June 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120626133319/http://www.entertainmentwise.com/news/79316/Cheryl-Cole-Confirms-Second-Single-From-A-Million-Lights |archivedate=26 June 2012  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Under-The-Sun/dp/B008YWPU8S/ |title=Under the Sun: Cheryl |publisher=Amazon.co.uk |date=1 January 1970 |accessdate=29 August 2012}}</ref> and peaked at number 13, becoming her seventh consecutive solo top-twenty single. To promote ''A Million Lights'', Cheryl embarked on her first solo concert tour, [[A Million Lights Tour]]. The tour ran from 3 to 17 October 2012, and comprised 11 show dates: two in Ireland, one in Scotland and eight in England. She also did a set of meet and greets at each concert. The £350 offer included an autograph, a chance to meet her and a photograph with her backstage, with proceeds going towards her charity, The Cheryl Cole Foundation. The meet and greet ticket drew negative criticism from fans, who complained about the high price.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-news/9330924/Cheryl-Cole-criticised-over-350-meet-and-greet-gig-tickets.html |title=Cheryl Cole criticised over £350 meet and greet gig tickets |publisher=Telegraph Media Group |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=14 June 2012 |accessdate=1 May 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805095925/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-news/9330924/Cheryl-Cole-criticised-over-350-meet-and-greet-gig-tickets.html |archivedate=5 August 2017  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Brett |last=Gibbons |url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/local-news/cheryl-cole-slammed-for-350-meet-186855 |title=Cheryl Cole slammed for £350 'meet and greet' at Birmingham LG Arena |publisher=Trinity Mirror |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=14 June 2012 |accessdate=1 May 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170804052857/http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/local-news/cheryl-cole-slammed-for-350-meet-186855 |archivedate=4 August 2017  }}</ref>

On 4 June 2012, Cheryl performed a duet with [[Gary Barlow]] at the [[Diamond Jubilee Concert]], which was organised and created by Barlow as part of the [[Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II]] and watched by millions worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mrpaparazzi.com/post/19353/Lets-talk-about-Cheryl-Coles-live-Jubilee-performance-with-Gary-Barlow|title=Let's talk about Cheryl Cole's live Jubilee performance with Gary Barlow 5 June 2012|publisher=Mrpaparazzi.com|accessdate=20 October 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120607212043/http://www.mrpaparazzi.com/post/19353/Lets-talk-about-Cheryl-Coles-live-Jubilee-performance-with-Gary-Barlow|archivedate=7 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.entertainmentwise.com/news/77614/Cheryl-Cole-Defends-Dire-Jubilee-Performance-It-Was-A-Dream |title=Cheryl Cole Defends Dire Jubilee Performance: 'It Was A Dream' 6 June 2012 |publisher=Entertainmentwise.com |date=6 June 2012 |accessdate=20 October 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107052145/http://www.entertainmentwise.com/news/77614/Cheryl-Cole-Defends-Dire-Jubilee-Performance-It-Was-A-Dream |archivedate=7 November 2012 |df= }}</ref> In 2012, Cheryl returned to ''The X Factor'' as a guest mentor to help Barlow pick his contestants for the live shows of the competition. In November 2012, she was handed her own documentary entitled ''Cheryl: Access All Areas'', which attracted 811,000 viewers on ITV2 and 177,000 on +1.<ref>{{cite web|last=Millar|first=Paul|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a439838/cheryl-coles-itv2-show-attracts-more-than-800000-viewers.html|title=Cheryl Cole's ITV2 show attracts more than 800,000 viewers|work=Digital Spy|date=21 November 2012|accessdate=31 August 2013|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130923032630/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a439838/cheryl-coles-itv2-show-attracts-more-than-800000-viewers.html|archivedate=23 September 2013}}</ref>

In November 2012, after months of speculation, Girls Aloud reunited for the group's 10th anniversary. On 18 November, they released their comeback single, "[[Something New (Girls Aloud song)|Something New]]", which was also the official charity single for ''[[Children in Need 2012]]''. The single peaked at number two on the UK Singles Chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/1/2012-12-01/|title=Top 40 Official UK Singles Archive|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=26 November 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121206030208/http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/1/2012-12-01|archivedate=6 December 2012}}</ref> The group released their second [[Greatest hits album|greatest hits compilation]], ''[[Ten (Girls Aloud album)|Ten]]'', on 26 November 2012. The second single taken from ''Ten'', "[[Beautiful Cause You Love Me]]", was released on 17 December.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a437776/girls-aloud-premiere-new-single-beautiful-cause-you-love-me-listen.html|title=Girls Aloud premier new single, 'Beautiful 'Cause You Love Me' – Listen|work=Digital Spy|date=13 November 2012|accessdate=14 November 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121115213521/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a437776/girls-aloud-premiere-new-single-beautiful-cause-you-love-me-listen.html|archivedate=15 November 2012}}</ref> A documentary entitled ''[[Girls Aloud: Ten Years at the Top]]'' aired on ITV1 on 15 December<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/presscentre/tenyearsofgirlsaloud/week51/default.html|title=Girls Aloud: Ten Years At The Top|work=ITV Press Centre|publisher=ITV|accessdate=1 December 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121216043003/http://www.itv.com/presscentre/tenyearsofgirlsaloud/week51/default.html|archivedate=16 December 2012}}</ref> and attracted 2.3&nbsp;million viewers, a 10.5% share of the audience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a445528/celebrity-take-me-out-pulls-in-38m-viewers.html|title=Celebrity 'Take Me Out' pulls in 3.8m viewers|author=Millar, Paul|work=Digital Spy|date=16 December 2012|accessdate=10 August 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140907223012/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a445528/celebrity-take-me-out-pulls-in-38m-viewers.html|archivedate=7 September 2014}}</ref> In 2013, the group embarked on [[Ten: The Hits Tour]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metroradioarena.co.uk/events/girls-aloud-ten-the-hits-tour-2013-with-special-guest-amelia-lily/|title=Girls Aloud reveal reunion plans|last=Savage|first=Mark|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=19 October 2012|date=19 October 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160430203416/http://www.metroradioarena.co.uk/events/girls-aloud-ten-the-hits-tour-2013-with-special-guest-amelia-lily/|archivedate=30 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metroradioarena.co.uk/events/girls-aloud-ten-the-hits-tour-2013-with-special-guest-amelia-lily/|title=Girls Aloud 'Ten – The Hits Tour 2013' with special guest Amelia Lily|publisher=[[Metro Radio Arena]]accessdate=3 August 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160430203416/http://www.metroradioarena.co.uk/events/girls-aloud-ten-the-hits-tour-2013-with-special-guest-amelia-lily/|archivedate=30 April 2016}}</ref> In March 2013, following the completion of the tour, Girls Aloud released a statement to confirm that they were splitting permanently.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/mar/21/girls-aloud-split|title=Girls Aloud split after final UK show|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=28 July 2013|date=21 March 2013|location=London|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002212912/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/mar/21/girls-aloud-split|archivedate=2 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-news/9945306/Girls-Aloud-split-up-after-last-night-of-tour.html|title=Girls Aloud split up after last night of tour|author=Lachno, James|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=28 July 2013|date=21 March 2013|location=London|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130603065529/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-news/9945306/Girls-Aloud-split-up-after-last-night-of-tour.html|archivedate=3 June 2013}}</ref>

===2014–2017: ''Only Human'' and ''The X Factor'' return===
In June 2014, Cheryl debuted the first single from her fourth studio album ''[[Only Human (Cheryl album)|Only Human]]'', "[[Crazy Stupid Love (song)|Crazy Stupid Love]]", which features [[Tinie Tempah]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.capitalfm.com/artists/cheryl-cole/news/crazy-stupid-love-first-play/|title=Cheryl Cole's new song 'Crazy, Stupid, Love' hailed as "amazing" after first play|last=|first=|date=2 June 2014|work=Capital FM|access-date=2 May 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170803215737/http://www.capitalfm.com/artists/cheryl-cole/news/crazy-stupid-love-first-play/|archivedate=3 August 2017}}</ref> Later in the month, she performed at [[Summertime Ball|Capital FM's Summertime Ball]] at [[Wembley Stadium]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/06/22/capital-summertime-ball-miley-cyrus-cheryl-cole-pics_n_5518966.html|title=Capital Summertime Ball 2014: Miley Cyrus and Cheryl Cole lead acts taking to the stage at Wembley Stadium|last=Welsh|first=Daniel|date=22 June 2014|work=The Huffington Post|access-date=2 May 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170621221717/http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/06/22/capital-summertime-ball-miley-cyrus-cheryl-cole-pics_n_5518966.html|archivedate=21 June 2017}}</ref> "Crazy Stupid Love" was officially released in July and entered the UK Singles Chart at number one, selling 118,000 copies. It became Cheryl's fourth number one single on the chart, making her the third British female artist to achieve four numbers ones as a solo artist, after [[Geri Halliwell]] and [[Rita Ora]].<ref name="cole's number 1 2014">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-28514580|title=Cheryl Cole lands fourth solo chart topper|publisher=BBC|date=27 July 2014|accessdate=9 August 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140811044546/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-28514580|archivedate=11 August 2014}}</ref> The song also peaked at number one in Ireland.<ref name="irish chart"/> The second single from ''Only Human'', "[[I Don't Care (Cheryl song)|I Don't Care]]", was released on 2 November and similarly to its predecessor debuted at number one in the UK, becoming Cheryl's fifth number one in the country. This made her the first British female to have five solo number one singles in the UK, and she held the record for the British female solo artist with the most UK number-one singles until [[Jess Glynne]] overtook her in 2018.<ref name="I don't care number one">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/cheryl-scores-record-breaking-fifth-number-1-single-with-i-dont-care-3270/|title=Cheryl scores record-breaking fifth Number 1 single with I Don't Care|last=Copsey|first=Rob|date=9 November 2014|publisher=Official Charts Company|accessdate=9 November 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109212007/http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/cheryl-scores-record-breaking-fifth-number-1-single-with-i-dont-care-3270/|archivedate=9 November 2014}}</ref><ref name="jess glynne record 2018">{{Cite news|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/jess-glynne-becomes-the-first-british-female-solo-artist-to-score-six-uk-number-1-singles__22407/|title=Jess Glynne makes UK chart history with sixth Number 1 single|last=|first=|date=30 March 2018|work=|access-date=9 November 2018|language=en}}</ref> ''Only Human'' was released on 10 November and became Cheryl's fourth solo album to debut within the top 10 in the United Kingdom and Ireland.<ref name="uk chart"/><ref name="irish chart"/> It was later certified silver in the UK.<ref name="bpi"/> The album's [[Only Human (Cheryl song)|title track]] was released as its third and final single in March 2015. The song, which originally peaked at number 70 as an album cut in October 2014, failed to reach the top 100 on the UK Singles Chart upon the single's release, therefore becoming Cheryl's lowest-charting single to date.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Duke|first1=Simon|title=Disaster for Cheryl Fernandez-Versini as Only Human fails to reach the top 100|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/whats-on/music-nightlife-news/disaster-cheryl-fernandez-versini-only-human-8945220|accessdate=30 March 2015|work=[[Chronicle Extra]]|agency=[[Trinity Mirror]]|date=30 March 2015|location=United Kingdom|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150331084342/http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/whats-on/music-nightlife-news/disaster-cheryl-fernandez-versini-only-human-8945220|archivedate=31 March 2015}}</ref>

In 2014, the singer also returned as a judge on the UK version of ''The X Factor'' for its [[The X Factor (UK series 11)|11th series]] to replace [[Sharon Osbourne]], signing a £1.5&nbsp;million contract.<ref name="X Factor 2014 (Billboard)">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/5930387/cheryl-cole-to-return-to-x-factor-uk|title=Cheryl Cole to Return to 'X Factor' U.K.|last=Amabile Angermiller|first=Michele|date=11 March 2014|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=11 March 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140829120923/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/5930387/cheryl-cole-to-return-to-x-factor-uk|archivedate=29 August 2014}}</ref><ref name="X Factor 2014 (THR)">{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/cheryl-cole-returns-x-factor-687400|title=Cheryl Cole to Return to 'X Factor' U.K.|last=Amabile Angermiller|first=Michele|date=10 March 2014|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=11 March 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140501095309/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/cheryl-cole-returns-x-factor-687400|archivedate=1 May 2014}}</ref> She was joined by Simon Cowell, Louis Walsh and [[Mel B]] on the judging panel. She was again selected to mentor the girls category, with her final act [[Lauren Platt]] coming fourth. In 2015, Cheryl returned to ''The X Factor'' for its [[The X Factor (UK series 12)|12th series]]; she was joined by Cowell and new judges Ora and [[Nick Grimshaw]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-33132895|title=''X Factor'': Nick Grimshaw and Rita Ora sign up as judges|date=16 June 2015|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=16 June 2015|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ZLyRWKAl?url=http://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-33132895|archivedate=17 June 2015|deadurl=yes}}</ref> She was selected to mentor the groups category for the first time and her last remaining group [[Reggie 'n' Bollie]] reached the final finishing in second place. Cheryl announced her departure from ''The X Factor'' in April 2016, choosing to focus on her music career; she was replaced by Osbourne.<ref name="Cheryl Quits (April 2016)">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/the-x-factor/news/a789388/cheryl-quits-the-x-factor-to-focus-on-her-pop-career/|title=It's OFFICIAL: Cheryl Fernandez-Versini quits ''The X Factor'' to focus on her pop career|date=5 April 2016|website=Digital Spy|author=Nissim, Mayer|accessdate=5 April 2016|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6gYO08UaA?url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/the-x-factor/news/a789388/cheryl-quits-the-x-factor-to-focus-on-her-pop-career/|archivedate=6 April 2016|deadurl=yes}}</ref> She guest appeared in the show's [[The X Factor (UK series 14)|14th series]] in 2017 as Cowell's adviser during the Judges' houses stage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/the-x-factor/news/a840055/cheryl-tweedy-x-factor-return-simon-cowell-judges-houses/|title=Cheryl IS returning to The X Factor this year to help Simon Cowell at Judges' Houses|work=[[Digital Spy]]|
date=7 October 2017|accessdate=26 July 2018}}</ref>

===2018: Fifth studio album and ''The Greatest Dancer''===
In July 2018, Cheryl revealed that her fifth studio album was "pretty much finished". She worked on the record with [[Naughty Boy]] and her former bandmate Nicola Roberts with whom she co-wrote every song.<ref>{{cite web|author= Rob Copsey|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/cheryl-reveals-her-new-album-is-nearly-finished-and-she-wrote-every-track-with-girls-alouds-nicola-roberts__23353/|title=Cheryl reveals her new album is nearly finished and she wrote every track with Girls Aloud's Nicola Roberts|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|date=11 July 2018|accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref> The album's first single, "[[Love Made Me Do It (song)|Love Made Me Do It]]", was released on 9 November 2018, and marked the singer's first release with new record label [[3 Beat Records|3 Beat]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Copsey |first=Rob |title=Cheryl's comeback single will be released this week |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/cheryl-confirms-new-single-love-made-me-do-it-release-date__24662/ |accessdate=6 November 2018 |work=[[Official Charts Company]] |date=6 November 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107021744/https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/cheryl-confirms-new-single-love-made-me-do-it-release-date__24662/ |archivedate=7 November 2018 |deadurl=no |location=United Kingdom }}</ref> It charted at number 19 in the UK, and number 32 in Ireland.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ainsley|first=Helen|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ariana-grandes-thank-u-next-claims-a-second-week-at-number-1-with-huge-streaming-numbers__24739/|title=Ariana Grande's thank u, next claims a second week at Number 1 with huge streaming numbers|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|date=16 November 2018|accessdate=21 November 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181121021425/https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ariana-grandes-thank-u-next-claims-a-second-week-at-number-1-with-huge-streaming-numbers__24739/|archivedate=21 November 2018}}</ref><ref name="irish chart">{{cite web|url=http://irish-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Cheryl+Cole|title=irishcharts.com – Discography Cheryl Cole|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref> Cheryl's performance of the song on [[The X Factor (UK series 15)|the 15th series]] of ''The X Factor'' was widely criticised in the media, with viewers arguing that its "overtly sexual nature" was "inappropriate" for [[Watershed (broadcasting)|pre-watershed]] television.<ref>{{cite web|last=Arnold|first=Ben|url=https://uk.news.yahoo.com/ofcom-mulls-investigation-complaints-cheryl-coles-raunchy-x-factor-show-085724397.html|title=Ofcom mulls investigation after complaints over Cheryl's 'raunchy' X Factor show|publisher=[[Yahoo!]]|date=20 November 2018|accessdate=20 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Vincent|first=Alice|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/artists/nations-sweetheart-pariah-britain-has-turned-cheryl/|title=From nation's sweetheart to pariah: why Britain has turned on Cheryl |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=London|date=21 November 2018|accessdate=21 November 2018|subscription=yes}}</ref> Following the single's release, the singer's label announced that they intend to release a series of singles before releasing a full-length album, with two singles being scheduled for the first quarter of 2019.<ref>{{cite web|last=Copsey|first=Rob|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/cheryls-love-made-me-do-it-debuts-at-number-1-on-the-official-trending-chart__24705/|title=Cheryl's Love Made Me Do It debuts at Number 1 on the Official Trending Chart|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|date=12 November 2018|accessdate=15 November 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115214519/https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/cheryls-love-made-me-do-it-debuts-at-number-1-on-the-official-trending-chart__24705/|archivedate=15 November 2018}}</ref> Cheryl will serve as a dance captain on the new [[BBC One]] dance competition ''[[The Greatest Dancer]]'' alongside [[Matthew Morrison]] and [[Oti Mabuse]]. The show will air in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|author=Susannah Alexander|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/reality-tv/news/a863639/cheryl-confirmed-dance-captain-greatest-dancer/|title=Cheryl confirmed as Dance Captain for The Greatest Dancer|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=10 August 2018|accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref>

==Other ventures==
As a member of Girls Aloud, Cheryl teamed with Eylure to release five sets of [[eyelash extensions|false eyelashes]], each set designed by a different member of the group. A range of [[music festival|festival]]-themed lashes followed in 2010, while limited edition "10th Anniversary" lash was released in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marieclaire.co.uk/news/beauty/451772/girls-aloud-launch-festival-false-lashes.html|title=Girls Aloud launch festival false lashes|author=Hutchings, Lucy|work=[[Marie Claire]]|date=22 April 2010|accessdate=20 November 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130710052129/http://www.marieclaire.co.uk/news/beauty/451772/girls-aloud-launch-festival-false-lashes.html|archivedate=10 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.reveal.co.uk/miss-mode-fashion-beauty/news/a432751/girls-aloud-launch-limited-edition-false-lashes-to-celebrate-reunion.html|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130421053810/http://m.reveal.co.uk/miss-mode-fashion-beauty/news/a432751/girls-aloud-launch-limited-edition-false-lashes-to-celebrate-reunion.html|dead-url=yes|archive-date=21 April 2013|title=Girls Aloud launch limited edition false lashes to celebrate reunion|author=Ascroft, Amber|work=Reveal|publisher=[[Nat Mags]]|date=23 October 2012|accessdate=20 November 2012}}</ref> Similarly, to celebrate their tenth anniversary, each member designed a [[charm bracelet]] for Pandora, available as either a complete bracelet or a "starter" bracelet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marieclaire.co.uk/news/celebrity/539060/cheryl-cole-designs-charm-bracelet-to-celebrate-girls-aloud-anniversary.html#index=1|title=Cheryl Cole designs charm bracelet to celebrate Girls Aloud anniversary|last=Twomey|first=Rebecca|publisher=Marie Claire|date=24 October 2012|accessdate=20 November 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121027202113/http://www.marieclaire.co.uk/news/celebrity/539060/cheryl-cole-designs-charm-bracelet-to-celebrate-girls-aloud-anniversary.html#index=1|archivedate=27 October 2012}}</ref>

Cheryl's first official book, entitled ''Through My Eyes'', was published on 30 September 2010 by [[Bantam Press]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.booksattransworld.co.uk/catalog/book.htm?command=Search&db=twmain.txt&eqisbndata=0593066383 |title=Book details for Through My Eyes by Cheryl Cole |work=[[Transworld (company)|Transworld]] |publisher=[[Random House]] |accessdate=4 September 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927162545/http://www.booksattransworld.co.uk/catalog/book.htm?command=Search&db=twmain.txt&eqisbndata=0593066383 |archivedate=27 September 2011 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/d/cka/Through-My-Eyes-Cheryl-Cole/0593066383|title=Through My Eyes|publisher=[[Amazon.co.uk]]|accessdate=3 August 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170803220155/https://www.amazon.co.uk/d/cka/Through-My-Eyes-Cheryl-Cole/0593066383|archivedate=3 August 2017}}</ref> ''Through My Eyes'' purports to show her in the recording studio, backstage on tour, behind-the-scenes at ''The X Factor'', at photo shoots and at award ceremonies. She said the book is "filled with pictures that capture those moments, [her] memories and the people [she's] closest to".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/cbbcnews/hi/newsid_8960000/newsid_8967200/8967258.stm|title=Cheryl Cole's bringing out behind-the-scenes photo book|work=[[CBBC]] [[Newsround]]|publisher=BBC|date=3 September 2010|accessdate=4 September 2010|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100905215043/http://news.bbc.co.uk/cbbcnews/hi/newsid_8960000/newsid_8967200/8967258.stm|archivedate=5 September 2010}}</ref> She is the subject of several unauthorised biographies,<ref>{{cite book|title=Cheryl Cole: Her Story – The Unauthorized Biography|work=[[Amazon.co.uk]]|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]|isbn=1843173891}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Cheryl|work=Amazon.co.uk|publisher=Amazon.com|isbn=1847372783}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Cheryl Cole: Promise: Star of Girls Aloud and The X Factor|work=Amazon.co.uk|publisher=Amazon.com|isbn=1409113620}}</ref> as well as books detailing her relationship with and divorce from Ashley Cole.<ref>{{cite book|title=Cheryl vs Ashley: When Love Dies|publisher=Amazon.com|isbn=1843174995}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Cheryl and Ashley – Love Wars|work=Amazon.com|isbn=1843581957 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/ashley-cheryl-cole-where-did/id379404025?mt=8 |title=Ashley and Cheryl Cole – Where Did It All Go Wrong? |publisher=Apple Inc. |date=30 June 2010 |accessdate=3 August 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111222456/https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/ashley-cheryl-cole-where-did/id379404025?mt=8 |archivedate=11 November 2012 |df= }}</ref> Her autobiography, ''[[Cheryl: My Story]]'', was published on 11 October 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.stv.tv/showbiz/314790-cheryl-cole-believed-doctors-were-trying-to-kill-her |title=Cheryl Cole believed doctors were trying to kill her|publisher=STV|date=8 October 2012|accessdate=20 October 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121213222453/http://entertainment.stv.tv/showbiz/314790-cheryl-cole-believed-doctors-were-trying-to-kill-her/|archivedate=13 December 2012}}</ref> The book's content was about her relationships with Simon Cowell and her ex-husband Cole.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cheryl warned ex husband over 'tell all book'|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news/cheryl-cole-warned-ex-husband-over-tell-all-book_1411919|date=September 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120912040853/http://www.contactmusic.com/news/cheryl-cole-warned-ex-husband-over-tell-all-book_1411919|archivedate=12 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Cheryl Cole on 'tell all' biography: 'Some people should be scared'|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/showbiz/news/a405257/cheryl-cole-on-tell-all-autobiography-some-people-should-be-scared.html|work=Digital Spy|accessdate=12 September 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120913073104/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/showbiz/news/a405257/cheryl-cole-on-tell-all-autobiography-some-people-should-be-scared.html|archivedate=13 September 2012}}</ref> It has sold 275,000 copies {{as of|2013|February|lc=y}}, generating £2.5&nbsp;million in sales. In August 2014, Cheryl released her debut fragrance, [[StormFlower]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/cheryl-cole/news/cheryl-cole-confirms-plans-to-release-debut-fragrance|title=Cheryl Cole Confirms Plans To Release Debut Fragrance|publisher=MTV|date=7 May 2014|accessdate=7 May 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512223536/http://www.mtv.co.uk/cheryl-cole/news/cheryl-cole-confirms-plans-to-release-debut-fragrance|archivedate=12 May 2014}}</ref>

===Philanthropy===
In 2004, Girls Aloud released a cover of [[The Pretenders]]' "[[I'll Stand by You]]" as the official single for the BBC's charity telethon ''[[Children in Need 2004|Children in Need]]''.<ref name="cincbbc">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/cbbcnews/hi/music/newsid_3986000/3986493.stm|title=Girls Aloud help Children in Need|work=Newsround|publisher=BBC|date=5 November 2004|accessdate=28 February 2008|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080307173314/http://news.bbc.co.uk/cbbcnews/hi/music/newsid_3986000/3986493.stm|archivedate=7 March 2008}}</ref> In 2007, the group announced a joint release of [[Aerosmith]] and [[Run DMC]]'s "[[Walk This Way]]" with [[Sugababes]] as the official single for the UK's other major charity telethon [[Comic Relief]]. The song was recorded at Comic Relief co-founder and trustee [[Richard Curtis]]' request.<ref name="crbbc">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6317377.stm|title=Girl groups get red noses rolling|publisher=BBC News|date=31 July 2007|accessdate=31 August 2010|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69lXaZa7l?url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6317377.stm|archivedate=8 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=The Singles Boxset|others=Girls Aloud|year=2009|chapter=Walk This Way|author=Robinson, Peter|authorlink=Peter Robinson (journalist)|page=35|type=Booklet|publisher=Fascination Records|location=London}}</ref>

In March 2009, Cheryl climbed [[Mount Kilimanjaro]] in aid of Comic Relief. The climb, organised by Gary Barlow, was also undertaken by fellow Girls Aloud member Kimberley Walsh, as well as [[Alesha Dixon]], [[Fearne Cotton]], [[Denise Van Outen]], [[Chris Moyles]], [[Ben Shephard]], [[Ronan Keating]] and Barlow himself.<ref>{{cite news |first=Vanessa |last=Thorpe |first2=Caroline |last2=Davies |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/mar/08/comic-relief-celebrities-kilimanjaro |title=Stars beat the pain barrier to conquer Kilimanjaro |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=8 March 2009 |accessdate=1 May 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170219001629/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/mar/08/comic-relief-celebrities-kilimanjaro |archivedate=19 February 2017  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/devon/7929954.stm |title=Red Nose leader's joy at summit |publisher=BBC |work=BBC News |date=7 March 2009 |accessdate=1 May 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090310134743/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/devon/7929954.stm |archivedate=10 March 2009  }}</ref> Between 3 February and 23 March 2009, Cheryl, Walsh, Barlow, Moyles and Cotton also raised money for Comic Relief by providing the voice for the [[BT Speaking Clock]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.newtownabbeytoday.co.uk/news/comic-relief-for-gemma-1-1698244 |title=Comic Relief for Gemma |newspaper=Newtownabbey Times |publisher= |date=18 March 2009 |accessdate=1 May 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171016122029/http://www.newtownabbeytoday.co.uk/news/comic-relief-for-gemma-1-1698244 |archivedate=16 October 2017  }}</ref> All nine celebrities reached the summit of Kilimanjaro on Saturday, 7 March 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7929888.stm|title=Celebrity climbers reach summit|publisher=BBC News|date=7 March 2009|accessdate=15 March 2009|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090317001111/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7929888.stm|archivedate=17 March 2009}}</ref> Cheryl, along with Cotton, Van Outen and Shephard, reached the summit first at sunrise. The trek raised £3.5&nbsp;million for the charity. In February 2011, Cheryl launched her own charitable foundation with [[The Prince's Trust]] following a meeting with The Trust's President, HRH [[Charles, Prince of Wales]]. The Cheryl Cole Foundation is meant to provide vital funds for The Trust in the North East, which was set up to help disadvantaged young people from Cheryl's region.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.princes-trust.org.uk/the_cheryl_cole_foundation.aspx |title=The Cheryl Cole Foundation|work=The Prince's Trust|accessdate=22 February 2011|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110224162220/http://princes-trust.org.uk/the_cheryl_cole_foundation.aspx|archivedate=24 February 2011}}</ref> On 13 June 2011, she auctioned 20 dresses with [[ASOS.com|ASOS]] to raise funds for the foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theappointment.co.uk/news/?submitted=False&ID=7053 |title=ASOS launches Cheryl Cole clothing auction for charity |publisher=TheAppointment.co.uk |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130728102658/http://www.theappointment.co.uk/news/?submitted=False&ID=7053 |archivedate=28 July 2013  }}</ref>

In September 2011, Cheryl became the latest "[[Forces sweetheart|Forces' sweetheart]]" when she visited [[British soldiers]] in Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cole becomes Forces' sweetheart|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/news/cole-becomes-forces-sweetheart-28658514.html|publisher=Belfast Telegraph|date=9 December 2016}}</ref> On 23 January 2015, Cheryl announced the launch of a second charity, once again alongside The Prince's Trust. The charity was named Cheryl's Trust, and was set up with the aim of raising £2&nbsp;million to build a centre, which will support up to 4000 disadvantaged young people in her native city of Newcastle.<ref>{{cite web|title=Partnership launch|url=http://cherylstrust.com/partnership-launch/|website=Cheryl's Trust|publisher=Cheryl's Trust|accessdate=27 December 2015|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105142453/http://cherylstrust.com/partnership-launch/|archivedate=5 January 2016}}</ref> To raise these funds, Cheryl has thus far teamed up with [[Prizeo]] in March 2015, setting up a styling session competition,<ref>{{cite web|title=Win a styling session with Cheryl!|url=http://cherylstrust.com/win-a-styling-session-with-cheryl-now-closed/|website=Cheryl's Trust|publisher=Cheryl's Trust|accessdate=27 December 2015|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105165035/http://cherylstrust.com/win-a-styling-session-with-cheryl-now-closed/|archivedate=5 January 2016}}</ref> and also launched a limited edition [[Belgian chocolate|Belgian Chocolate]] Bar with [[Greggs]] in August 2015; 5p proceeds from each sale being donated towards the trust.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gregg's launch limited edition chocolate bar in aid of Cheryl's Trust|url=http://cherylstrust.com/greggs-launch-limited-edition-chocolate-bar-in-aid-of-cheryls-trust/|website=Cheryl's Trust|publisher=Cheryl's Trust|accessdate=27 December 2015|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105133733/http://cherylstrust.com/greggs-launch-limited-edition-chocolate-bar-in-aid-of-cheryls-trust/|archivedate=5 January 2016}}</ref> In November 2016, she became the ambassador of the charity [[ChildLine]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Cheryl to be new face of Childline|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-37839500|website=BBC News|publisher=BBC|date=2 November 2016|accessdate=3 November 2016|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161102235926/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-37839500|archivedate=2 November 2016}}</ref>

==Artistry and influences==
Cheryl has a [[mezzo-soprano]] range.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-18265975|title=Cheryl: 'I'm happy if people think I'm miming'|publisher=BBC|date=7 June 2012|accessdate=8 June 2012|first=Mark|last=Savage|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120607230741/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-18265975|archivedate=7 June 2012}}</ref>
She spoke about her vocal ability saying, "I am very aware of my ability, I know I'm no [[Mariah Carey]] but I think the emotion in the song is what matters."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/news/cheryl-cole/356772-cheryl-cole-mariah-carey-arena-tour-wretch-32-screw-you|title=Cheryl Cole: "I'm no Mariah Carey"|publisher=MTV|date=31 May 2012|accessdate=16 July 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616053212/http://www.mtv.co.uk/news/cheryl-cole/356772-cheryl-cole-mariah-carey-arena-tour-wretch-32-screw-you|archivedate=16 June 2012}}</ref> ''3 Words'' was influenced by her appreciation for dance music and crosses from contemporary R&B, dance pop, house and a more general pop sound. ''Messy Little Raindrops'' uses a more dance pop sound than her previous album. ''A Million Lights'', her third studio album also incorporates R&B and dance.<ref name="Entertainment Wise">{{cite web|url=http://www.entertainmentwise.com/news/76603/Cheryl-Coles-New-Material-Inspired-By-Volatile-Relationships |title=Cheryl Cole's New Material Inspired by Volatile Relationships |publisher=Entertanmentwise.com |accessdate=31 May 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120527051911/http://www.entertainmentwise.com/news/76603/Cheryl-Coles-New-Material-Inspired-By-Volatile-Relationships |archivedate=27 May 2012 |df= }}</ref> She incorporated [[Dubstep]] into ''A Million Lights'', [[MTV]] citing "Girl in the Mirror" as an example.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/news/cheryl-cole/355527-cheryl-cole-a-million-lights-album-cover-see-it-here|title=Cheryl Unveils New Album Cover & Tracklisting|publisher=MTV|accessdate=17 June 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928013608/http://www.mtv.co.uk/news/cheryl-cole/355527-cheryl-cole-a-million-lights-album-cover-see-it-here|archivedate=28 September 2013}}</ref>

Cheryl has named [[Britney Spears]] and [[Beyoncé]] as a few of her inspirations, performance and fashion-wise.<ref name="Get Music">{{cite web|url=http://www.getmusic.com.au/cherylcole/biography|title=GetMusic.com Cheryl Biography|publisher=Getmusic.com.au|accessdate=24 May 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110304041256/http://getmusic.com.au/cherylcole/biography|archivedate=4 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://skyliving.sky.com/cheryl-coles-body-inspiration |title=Cheryl's Body Inspiration |publisher=[[Sky Living]] |accessdate=16 June 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107052141/http://skyliving.sky.com/cheryl-coles-body-inspiration |archivedate=7 November 2012 |df= }}</ref> She spoke on the reason Beyoncé was an influence on her, saying, "I love Beyoncé, I just think she is such a beautiful person inside and out, apart from what she does on the stage which is obviously incredible and aspiration. I just like her as a woman. She's empowering."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.capitalfm.com/artists/cheryl-cole/news/beyonce-inspiration/|title=Cheryl Cole Inspired By Beyonce: "She's Such A Beautiful Person"|date=14 June 2012|work=Capital|publisher=Capital FM|accessdate=1 May 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170123140602/http://www.capitalfm.com/artists/cheryl-cole/news/beyonce-inspiration/|archivedate=23 January 2017}}</ref> She has cited [[Lisa Lopes|Lisa "Left Eye"' Lopes]], a former member of American band [[TLC (band)|TLC]], as another influence saying, "I wanted to be [Lopes] – I used to wear baggy jeans and Timberlands like a tomboy."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a405273/cheryl-cole-i-wanted-to-be-lisa-left-eye-lopes.html|title=Cheryl Cole: "I wanted to be Lisa 'Left Eye' Lopes"|date=11 September 2012|work=Digital Spy|accessdate=20 October 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111041604/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a405273/cheryl-cole-i-wanted-to-be-lisa-left-eye-lopes.html|archivedate=11 November 2012}}</ref> Other influences she has cited are Rihanna, whom she described as "a perfect pop star",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hollywoodhiccups.com/2012/05/08/cheryl-cole-admires-rihannas-confidence-she-doesnt-care-what-people-think-about-her|title=Cheryl Cole Admires Rihanna's Confidence: 'She Doesn't Care What People Think About Her'|accessdate=10 September 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120520131539/http://hollywoodhiccups.com/2012/05/08/cheryl-cole-admires-rihannas-confidence-she-doesnt-care-what-people-think-about-her/|archivedate=20 May 2012}}</ref> and [[Mary J. Blige]], saying, "Mary's voice sounds so grown up and you can hear that she has experienced a lot in her life, her songs help me with every heartache."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/news/cheryl-cole-my-music-isnt-lifechanging-16214184.html|title=Cheryl Cole: My music isn't life-changing|date=21 September 2012|work=The Belfast Telegraph|accessdate=20 October 2012}}</ref> Cheryl has influenced other artists, including [[Selena Gomez]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a284786/selena-gomez-influenced-by-cheryl-cole.html|title=Selena Gomez 'influenced by Cheryl Cole'|date=28 October 2010|work=Digital Spy|accessdate=20 October 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130610193244/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a284786/selena-gomez-influenced-by-cheryl-cole.html|archivedate=10 June 2013}}</ref> The 2006 [[Lily Allen]] song "Cheryl Tweedy" was written about her.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/04/29/lily-allen-cheryl-cole-feud-feminism-criticism-betrayed_n_5231154.html|title=Lily Allen Regrets Cheryl Cole Feud, But Feels 'Betrayed' By Criticism From Other Women|work=[[HuffPost]]|date=29 April 2014|accessdate=26 July 2018}}</ref>

=== Accusations of lip-syncing ===
It has been widely reported that Cheryl [[Lip sync|lip-syncs]] during live performances. Whilst performing "Fight for this Love" in 2009 on ''The X Factor'', media speculated that the performance was mimed, something that she denied though she admitted to having some pre-recorded vocals to help the live performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/artists/cheryl-cole/news/160107-cheryl-gives-incredible-x-factor-performance|title=Cheryl gives 'incredible' X Factor performance|work=MTV UK|date=19 October 2009|accessdate=25 October 2009|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091022153936/http://www.mtv.co.uk/artists/cheryl-cole/news/160107-cheryl-gives-incredible-x-factor-performance|archivedate=22 October 2009}}</ref> In 2010, during her second performance on ''The X Factor'', in which she performed "Promise This", she "showcased her vocal and dancing skills with an energetic, raunchy routine that earned a standing ovation from her fellow judges."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.stv.tv/tv/204658-cheryl-cole-lives-up-to-promise-as-she-shines-on-x-factor|title=Cheryl Cole lives up to Promise as she shines on X Factor|publisher=stv.tv|date=24 October 2010|accessdate=25 October 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101027192513/http://entertainment.stv.tv/tv/204658-cheryl-cole-lives-up-to-promise-as-she-shines-on-x-factor/|archivedate=27 October 2010}}</ref> Similar to her 2009 performance of "Fight for This Love" on ''The X Factor'', the media speculated whether she lip-synced or not. An ITV spokesperson insisted that she did not mime, although the performance was pre-recorded.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unrealitytv.co.uk/x-factor/x-factor-bosses-insist-cheryl-cole-didnt-mime-promise-this/|title=X Factor bosses insist Cheryl Cole DIDN'T mime 'Promise This'|publisher=Unreality TV|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140907222605/http://www.unrealitytv.co.uk/x-factor/x-factor-bosses-insist-cheryl-cole-didnt-mime-promise-this/|archivedate=7 September 2014}}</ref>

In June 2012, Cheryl performed "Call My Name" with live vocals on ''[[The Voice UK]]''. It was reported that ''The Voice'' executives always edit the vocals for every artist on the show, and they would "provide some finishing touches to her singing prior to it being broadcast." As the performance began, she swan-dived onto her backing dancers before they performed a highly elaborated routine. Following the broadcast, she received mixed comments from viewers, with a few accusing the singer of lip-synching, while others, including pop artists [[Emma Bunton]] and will.i.am, praised the performance. In an interview with [[BBC News]], she addressed the negative comments, and said that "if you think my live vocal sounds so good it must be mimed, I'm happy, I take it as a compliment."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-18265975|title=Cheryl: 'I'm happy if people think I'm miming'|date=7 June 2012|accessdate=11 June 2012|publisher=BBC News|author=Savage, Mark|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120610200740/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-18265975|archivedate=10 June 2012}}</ref>

==Public image==
[[File:Wax figure of Cheryl.jpg|thumb|upright|A wax figure of Cheryl at the museum [[Madame Tussauds]] in London]]
Cheryl has become a recognised and photographed style icon.<ref name="styletelegraph">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/celebritynews/5116123/Cheryl-Cole-voted-best-dressed-woman-and-style-icon-of-the-decade.html|title=Cheryl Cole voted best dressed woman and style icon of the decade|date=6 April 2009|work=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|accessdate=3 September 2009|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090411000320/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/celebritynews/5116123/Cheryl-Cole-voted-best-dressed-woman-and-style-icon-of-the-decade.html|archivedate=11 April 2009}}</ref><ref name="glamour">{{cite web|url=http://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/celebrity/news/daily-gossip/090409-cheryl-cole-is-glamours-best-dress.aspx |title=Cheryl is GLAMOUR's Best Dressed |date=9 April 2009 |work=Glamour |accessdate=3 September 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090413042335/http://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/celebrity/news/daily-gossip/090409-cheryl-cole-is-glamours-best-dress.aspx |archivedate=13 April 2009 |df= }}</ref><ref name="vogue">{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.co.uk/news/daily/090105-cheryl-cole-on-british-vogue-cover.aspx |title=Vogue's New Darling |date=5 January 2009 |quote=CHERYL COLE cements her style icon status |work=British Vogue |accessdate=3 September 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20110611164352/http://www.vogue.co.uk/news/daily/090105-cheryl-cole-on-british-vogue-cover.aspx |archivedate=11 June 2011 |df= }}</ref> Fashion magazine ''[[Vogue (British magazine)|British Vogue]]'' praised her style saying: "Her wardrobe choices have become as successful as her singles – while filming for ''The X Factor'', she had fashion fans watching her every sartorial move and was snapped wearing a string of fashion-forward outfits from [[Givenchy]] and Preen, to McQueen and [[Missoni]]."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.co.uk/spy/celebrity-photos/2010/11/22/style-file-cheryl-cole|title=Cheryl's fashion and style pictures (Vogue.com UK)|work=Vogue|date=22 November 2010|accessdate=20 October 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022114937/http://www.vogue.co.uk/spy/celebrity-photos/2010/11/22/style-file-cheryl-cole|archivedate=22 October 2012}}</ref> In both 2009 and 2010, she was named the best dressed woman by Glamour Magazine, after 14,000 votes from the magazine's readers were counted.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/8603059.stm|title=Cheryl Cole keeps 'best-dressed' crown in Glamour poll|publisher=BBC News|date=5 April 2010|accessdate=20 October 2012}}</ref> She has been photographed for the covers of ''British Vogue'',<ref name="vogue"/> ''[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]'' and ''[[Harper's Bazaar]]''. In March 2010, Cheryl was declared by research company [[Millward Brown]] as the second most powerful celebrity in Britain.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Kylie Minogue named 'most powerful celebrity in Britain' |publisher=The Daily Telegraph UK |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/7540790/Kylie-Minogue-named-most-powerful-celebrity-in-Britain.html |accessdate=31 March 2010 |location=London |date=31 March 2010}}</ref>

Cheryl topped [[FHM 100 Sexiest Women in the World]] in 2009 and 2010. She has won [[Glamour (magazine)#UK|Glamour Women of the Year Awards]] for TV Personality and Best Dressed<ref name="This is London">{{cite web|url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/showbiz/article-23703040-details/Cheryl+Cole+tops+Glamour%27s+TV+personality+poll/article.do |title=Cheryl Cole tops Glamour's TV personality poll |date=6 March 2009 |work=London Evening Standard |accessdate=28 June 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090923183631/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/showbiz/article-23703040-details/Cheryl%2BCole%2Btops%2BGlamour%27s%2BTV%2Bpersonality%2Bpoll/article.do |archivedate=23 September 2009 |df= }}</ref> and [[Style Network]] Award for Best Dressed Woman and Style Icon of the Decade.<ref name="styletelegraph" /> In February 2009, she appeared on the cover of ''British Vogue''. The media coverage of her appearance in the magazine boosted the magazine's circulation to 240,000, its best ever February figure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/feb/12/cheryl-cole-helps-lift-vogue-sales|title=Cheryl Cole helps lift Vogue sales|author=Brook, Stephen|date=12 February 2009|work=The Guardian|accessdate=28 June 2009|location=London|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140213230150/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/feb/12/cheryl-cole-helps-lift-vogue-sales|archivedate=13 February 2014}}</ref> She appeared on the November 2009 cover of the UK's ''Elle'' magazine. In October 2010, a wax statue of her was added to the gallery of [[Madame Tussauds London]] at a cost of approximately £150,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/news/cheryl-cole/242977-cheryl-cole-wax-work-girls-aloud-x-factor-simon-cowell|title=Cheryl Cole Unveils Waxwork at Madame Tussauds|publisher=MTV UK|date=20 October 2010|accessdate=31 August 2013}}</ref>

==Personal life==

Cheryl began dating England and Chelsea [[Association football|footballer]] Ashley Cole in September 2004, announcing their engagement after he proposed in Dubai in June 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/arts/2005/0617/tweedyc.html |title=Girls Aloud singer Tweedy gets engaged |publisher=[[Raidió Teilifís Éireann]] |date=17 June 2005 |accessdate=5 October 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100524091950/http://www.rte.ie/arts/2005/0617/tweedyc.html |archivedate=24 May 2010 |df= }}</ref> The couple were married at a ceremony at [[Chipping Barnet|Barnet]], north west London on 15 July 2006.<ref name=":0">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/5182542.stm|title=Tweedy and Cole in wedding ruse|date=15 July 2006|publisher=BBC|accessdate=12 November 2008|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071230040457/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/5182542.stm|archivedate=30 December 2007}}</ref> They signed an exclusive deal with ''[[OK!]]'', reportedly worth £1&nbsp;million, regarding the rights of the photographs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/arts/2006/0717/girlsaloud.html |title=Singer Tweedy marries footballer Cole |publisher=Raidió Teilifís Éireann |date=17 July 2006 |accessdate=5 October 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070913205903/http://www.rte.ie/arts/2006/0717/girlsaloud.html |archivedate=13 September 2007 |df= }}</ref> On 23 February 2010, Cheryl announced she was separating from Cole,<ref name="BBC News">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/8531260.stm|title=Cheryl Cole splits from footballer Ashley Cole|date=23 February 2010|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=1 March 2010|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100301153606/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/8531260.stm|archivedate=1 March 2010}}</ref><ref name="Official Statement">{{cite web|url=http://www.cherylcole.com/news/official-statement|title=Official Statement|publisher=Cheryl Cole Online|accessdate=28 February 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100227023024/http://www.cherylcole.com/news/official-statement/|archivedate=27 February 2010}}</ref> and on 26 May, she filed for divorce at [[High Court of Justice|London's High Court]] citing "unreasonable behaviour" from her estranged husband. The divorce papers state that Cole admitted being unfaithful to Cheryl with a number of other women.<ref name="Cheryl files for divorce">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/showbiz/news/a221838/cheryl-cole-files-for-divorce.html|title=Cheryl Cole 'files for divorce'|last=Kilkelly|first=Daniel|work=Digital Spy|accessdate=2 June 2010|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/679XWnpWr?url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/showbiz/news/a221838/cheryl-cole-files-for-divorce.html|archivedate=24 April 2012}}</ref> She was granted a [[decree nisi]] on 3 September.<ref name=":1">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-11173177|title=Cheryl and Ashley Cole granted divorce|publisher=BBC News|date=3 September 2010|accessdate=3 September 2010|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100903194843/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-11173177|archivedate=3 September 2010}}</ref> She continued to use her married name, but later began using the mononym Cheryl for her music releases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2010/oct/23/cheryl-cole-interview-simon-hattenstone|location=London|work=The Guardian|author=Hattenstone, Simon|title=Cheryl Cole: 'I hate this year'|date=23 October 2010|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221113913/https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2010/oct/23/cheryl-cole-interview-simon-hattenstone|archivedate=21 December 2016}}</ref>

On 7 July 2014, Cheryl married French restaurateur Jean-Bernard Fernandez-Versini after a three-month courtship.<ref name=":2">{{cite web|title=Cheryl Cole reveals secret marriage|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-28288707|accessdate=13 July 2014|publisher=BBC News|date=13 July 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714183914/http://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-28288707|archivedate=14 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=":3">{{cite web|author=Johnson, Zach|title=Surprise! Cheryl Cole Marries Jean-Bernard Fernandez-Versini—See Her Massive Diamond Ring!|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/559396/surprise-cheryl-cole-marries-jean-bernard-fernandez-versini-see-her-massive-diamond-ring|accessdate=14 July 2014|publisher=E! Online|date=14 July 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715023140/http://www.eonline.com/news/559396/surprise-cheryl-cole-marries-jean-bernard-fernandez-versini-see-her-massive-diamond-ring|archivedate=15 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=":4">{{cite web|author=Buchanan, Daisy|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/womens-life/10965756/Cheryl-Cole-secret-marriage-to-French-boyfriend-after-three-months.html|title=Cheryl Cole: why this whirlwind romance gives marriage a good name|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=London|date=14 July 2014|accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref> Following their separation, Cheryl began dating singer [[Liam Payne]] in early 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/cheryl-fernandez-versini-moves-in-with-liam-payne-116041000053_1.html|title=Cheryl Fernandez-Versini moves in with Liam Payne?|publisher=Business Standard|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414082834/http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/cheryl-fernandez-versini-moves-in-with-liam-payne-116041000053_1.html|archivedate=14 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/753881/liam-payne-and-cheryl-fernandez-versini-are-madly-in-love-and-very-happy-according-to-simon-cowell|title=Liam Payne and Cheryl Fernandez-Versini Are "Madly in Love" and "Very Happy," According to Simon Cowell|publisher=E! Online|author=Vulpo, Mike|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008105055/http://www.eonline.com/news/753881/liam-payne-and-cheryl-fernandez-versini-are-madly-in-love-and-very-happy-according-to-simon-cowell|archivedate=8 October 2016}}</ref> before being granted a decree nisi from Fernandez-Versini on 20 October 2016.<ref name=":5">{{cite web|author=Bacardi, Francesca|title=Cheryl Fernandez-Versini & Jean-Bernard Fernandez-Versini Are Divorced|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/803394/cheryl-fernandez-versini-and-jean-bernard-fernandez-versini-are-officially-divorced|accessdate=20 October 2016|publisher=[[NBCUniversal]]|date=20 October 2016|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6lP8aRkZ1?url=http://www.eonline.com/news/803394/cheryl-fernandez-versini-and-jean-bernard-fernandez-versini-are-officially-divorced|archivedate=20 October 2016|deadurl=yes }}</ref> On 22 March 2017, she gave birth to Payne's son.<ref name=":7">{{cite news|author1=Entertainment & Arts|title=Cheryl and Liam announce birth of baby boy|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-39395996|accessdate=25 March 2017|work=BBC News|date=25 March 2017|location=United Kingdom|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170326060246/http://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-39395996|archivedate=26 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Read-Dominguez|first1=Jennifer|title=Cheryl and Liam welcome their first child|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/showbiz/news/a823511/cheryl-fernandez-versini-liam-payne-welcome-first-baby/|website=Digital Spy|publisher=[[Hearst Corporation]]|accessdate=25 March 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170325212737/http://www.digitalspy.com/showbiz/news/a823511/cheryl-fernandez-versini-liam-payne-welcome-first-baby/|archivedate=25 March 2017|location=United Kingdom|language=en|date=25 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Bacardi|first1=Francesca|title=Liam Payne and Cheryl Cole Welcome First Child Together|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/827620/liam-payne-and-cheryl-cole-welcome-their-first-child-together|website=[[E! Online]]|publisher=NBCUniversal|accessdate=9 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170509140340/http://www.eonline.com/news/827620/liam-payne-and-cheryl-cole-welcome-their-first-child-together|archivedate=9 May 2017|location=United States|date=25 March 2017|dead-url=no}}</ref> Cheryl and Payne announced they had ended their relationship in July 2018.<ref name=":8">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-44677975|title=Cheryl and Liam Payne announce split|date=2018-07-01|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-07-01|language=en-GB}}</ref>

In December 2016, Cheryl appeared on the BBC One genealogy series ''[[Who Do You Think You Are? (UK TV series)|Who Do You Think You Are?]]'', during which she researched her maternal family.<ref>{{cite news |first=Gerard |last=O'Donovan |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2016/12/15/do-think-cheryl-looks-like-already-knew-review/ |title=Who Do You Think You Are, Cheryl? Looks like she already knew – review |publisher=Telegraph Media Group |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=15 December 2016 |accessdate=16 December 2016 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161216060324/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2016/12/15/do-think-cheryl-looks-like-already-knew-review/ |archivedate=16 December 2016  }}</ref> Research shows that her paternal line is from Tyneside<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thegenealogist.co.uk/featuredarticles/2016/who-do-you-think-you-are/cheryl-398/|title=Featured article on TheGenealogist|website=TheGenealogist|accessdate=16 December 2016|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220200616/https://www.thegenealogist.co.uk/featuredarticles/2016/who-do-you-think-you-are/cheryl-398/|archivedate=20 December 2016}}</ref> and that there were a number of coal miners amongst Cheryl's forebears. When tracing further back, in one of the branches of her paternal line, researchers find that her ancestry includes several mariners.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whodoyouthinkyouaremagazine.com/wdytya-episode-summary-cheryl|title=Who Do You Think You Are Magazine|website=whodoyouthinkyouaremagazine.com|accessdate=16 December 2016|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221015854/http://www.whodoyouthinkyouaremagazine.com/wdytya-episode-summary-cheryl|archivedate=21 December 2016}}</ref> The investigation into Cheryl's maternal line shows that her grandmother, Olga Ridley, was one of twin girls born to Edith Annie Burton, the housekeeper for a widower named Joseph Ridley who already had a number of children from his marriage.<ref name="thegenealogist.co.uk">{{cite web|url=https://www.thegenealogist.co.uk/featuredarticles/2016/who-do-you-think-you-are/cheryl-398/|title=TheGenealogist featured article on Cheryl|website=TheGenealogist|accessdate=16 December 2016|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220200616/https://www.thegenealogist.co.uk/featuredarticles/2016/who-do-you-think-you-are/cheryl-398/|archivedate=20 December 2016}}</ref> Joseph Ridley had fought in [[World War I]] in the [[Durham Light Infantry]] as a [[Pioneer (military)|Pioneer]] in France and, from an examination of the census, before the war he had been a Grocery Warehouseman.<ref name="thegenealogist.co.uk" />

===Assault conviction===
On 11 January 2003, Cheryl was involved in an altercation with a nightclub toilet attendant, Sophie Amogbokpa, and subsequently charged with racially aggravated assault over the incident.<ref>{{cite news|date=13 January 2003|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2651617.stm|title=Girls Aloud star 'not a racist'|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=14 August 2006|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228003920/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2651617.stm|archivedate=28 February 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/personal-view/3598357/Youre-not-a-racist-but-a-simple-thug-How-groovy-Cheryl.html|title=You're not a racist, but a simple thug? How groovy, Cheryl|first=Jenny|last=McCartney|publisher=|accessdate=12 March 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324233718/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/personal-view/3598357/Youre-not-a-racist-but-a-simple-thug-How-groovy-Cheryl.html|archivedate=24 March 2017}}</ref> At her trial on 20 October she was found guilty of [[Assault occasioning actual bodily harm#United Kingdom|assault occasioning actual bodily harm]] but cleared of the [[Crime and Disorder Act 1998#Racially or religiously aggravated offences|racially aggravated assault charge]],<ref name=BBCGui>{{cite news|date=20 October 2003|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/3207822.stm|title=Singer Tweedy guilty of assault|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=31 May 2006|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060524041044/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/3207822.stm|archivedate=24 May 2006}}</ref> and sentenced to 120 hours of [[community service]]. She was ordered to pay her victim £500 in [[Damages|compensation]], as well as £3,000 prosecution costs. Judge Richard Howard said, "This was an unpleasant piece of drunken violence which caused Sophie Amogbokpa pain and suffering."<ref name="BBCGui"/>

