{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}} {{Use British English|date=February 2016}} '''William Barber''' (1734–1805) was an English [[cricket]]er who played for the [[Hambledon Club]] in its great days during the 1760s and 1770s. Originally from [[Walberton]], near [[Chichester]], he came to Hambledon to play after being "spotted".<ref name=GDC>[[Ashley Mote]], ''The Glory Days of Cricket'', Robson, 1997</ref>
Barber finished playing in 1777. He is said to have bowled a "high delivery on a good length" and was probably a medium quick bowler.<ref name=JN>[[Ashley Mote]], ''John Nyren's "The Cricketers of my Time"'', Robson, 1998</ref>
His family and that of [[Thomas Brett (cricketer)|Thomas Brett]] were inter-married. Barber seems to have been a shoemaker but he latterly took over the ''[[Bat and Ball Inn]]'' (see also [[Broadhalfpenny Down]]) from [[Richard Nyren]]. He died aged 71 in 1805 and was buried in [[Catherington]].<ref name=GDC/>
